# UI icons (chrome vs static assets)

## Prefer inline SVG in React

For UI chrome icons (nav, theme sun/moon/auto, edit/cancel, logout, dialogs,
empty states, card header actions), use **inline SVG in React** — same style as
`ThemeSwitch`, `ProfileSectionHeader`, and `SidebarFooter`:

- `stroke="currentColor"` (or fill when the glyph is solid)
- `fill="none"` when stroked
- `aria-hidden="true"` when decorative; pair with a visible label or
  `aria-label` on the control
- Match existing size / stroke-width conventions in nearby components

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — chrome icon as inline SVG
<svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
  <path d="…" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="2" strokeLinecap="round" />
</svg>

// ❌ BAD — generated PNG for edit/cancel/logout chrome
<img src="/icon-edit.png" alt="" />
```

## When `public/` is appropriate

Put files under `public/` **only** for:

- Brand logos (`logo-full.svg`, `logo-mark.svg`, favicons)
- PWA / app icons (`icon-192`, `icon-512`, maskable, apple-touch)
- Avatars (`avatar-default.png` and user-uploaded/served avatars)
- Icons that must be shared as files (e.g. CSS `mask-image` →
  `icon-theme-auto.svg`)
- True raster UI assets that are intentionally referenced (e.g. channel status
  PNGs, calendar trigger art)

Name new static icons `public/icon-<purpose>.svg` or `.png` and **reference them
from code** in the same change. Do not leave unreferenced files in `public/`.

## User-provided assets

If the user supplies an icon file, use it **byte-identical**. Do **not** invent,
redraw, “improve,” or AI-generate a replacement.

## Cleanup

Do **not** keep unused generated or legacy UI icons in `public/` (e.g. old
`icon-edit.png`, `icon-cancel.png`, `icon-verified.png` once unreferenced).
When chrome moves to inline SVG, delete the orphaned asset in the same change.
